umor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/31151110/Hope-XCR-lightweight-mountain-bike-brakes_superlight-powerful-CNC-XC-Trail-MTB-brakeset_made-in-UK_405g-actual-weight-pair-696x418.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/31151110/Hope-XCR-lightweight-mountain-bike-brakes_superlight-powerful-CNC-XC-Trail-MTB-brakeset_made-in-UK_405g-actual-weight-pair-1068x641.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/31151110/Hope-XCR-lightweight-mountain-bike-brakes_superlight-powerful-CNC-XC-Trail-MTB-brakeset_made-in-UK_405g-actual-weight-pair-700x420.jpg 700w\"></a></p><p>A key focus on the new design is lighter weight. Claiming a total system weight from just 199g (lever, hose, caliper &amp; DOT 5.1 fluid) our test front brake came in under than that at 194g, without even shortening the brake line yet. The rear is just a bit over at 211g complete, before we get around to trimming several inches of hose to fit.</p><p>Hope says that many of their competitors like to share brake weight without fluid, so they gave us that figure for the XCR too, from 182g. Add to either of those numbers 16g of brake mounting bolts, plus 147g per wheel for the 180mm floating rotors we are running.</p><p><span data-ez-name=\"bikerumor_com-box-4\"></span>The actual combined front &amp; rear weight or 405g was 77g lighter than the XTR M988/985 brakes they replaced (252g rear, 230g front, cut to length), an impressive 16% weight savings.</p><h3>Hope XCR brakes – Pricing, options &amp; availability</h3><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/31151103/Hope-XCR-lightweight-mountain-bike-brakes_superlight-powerful-CNC-XC-Trail-MTB-brakeset_made-in-UK_XCR-X2-set.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/31151103/Hope-XCR-lightweight-mountain-bike-brakes_superlight